ABOUT

Few are aware of the origins of the term “blue chip,” which traces back to poker, where blue chips historically held the highest value. The term was later adopted in the financial world in the 1920s by Dow Jones employee Oliver Gingold to describe high-priced stocks. Over time, its meaning evolved to represent shares in large, stable, and reputable companies known for their quality and reliability—such as Microsoft, Coca-Cola, Apple, and Johnson &Johnson.

Today, the concept of blue chips has expanded beyond traditional equities to include assets such as real estate, bonds, collectibles, and even cryptocurrency.

While many coins claim blue-chip status, there is only one true Blue Chip.
